Language is important in influencing human mind because it allows people to express and convey their ideas and experiences. It enables individuals to organize their ideas, classify data, draw conclusions, and reason about the world. Language and mind are inextricably linked, according to cognitive psychology research, and the language we use may impact how we think about the world. For example, consider Lera Boroditsky's research on linguistic relativity, which holds that the language we use impacts our cognitive processes and changes our perception of the world. Boroditsky discovered that speakers of various languages conceive about time, location, and causality in different ways depending on their language's grammatical patterns. In one research, she discovered that speakers of English, which has a linear notion of time, prefer to conceive of time as a straight line moving forward, but speakers of Aymara, an indigenous South American language with a cyclical sense of time, think of time as repeated cycles. The Sapir-Whorf hypothesis is another example of research that demonstrates the importance of language on molding human mind. This hypothesis, presented by Edward Sapir and Benjamin Lee Whorf, contends that the structure of a language impacts how its speakers see and think about the world. They contended that the linguistic categories and differences present in a particular language influence how individuals classify and think about the world. For example, there is no differentiation between blue and green in certain languages, and persons who speak such languages are less likely to distinguish between the two hues. Finally, research has revealed that language plays an important part in molding human mind by allowing people to express and convey their ideas and experiences. It may impact how we classify and think about the world, as well as how we think about time, space, causality, and many other concepts and notions. Language and mind are inextricably linked, and the language we use may have a significant influence on how we see and comprehend the world around us. 